final List<Article> allArticles = [
  // --- ANXIOUS ARTICLES (10) ---
  Article(
    title: 'The 5-4-3-2-1 Grounding Method',
    description: 'A biological reset for your nervous system.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1518199266791-5375a83190b7?w=500',
    content: "Anxiety is often described as a 'future-based' emotion. Your mind is racing toward potential disasters that haven't happened yet. The 5-4-3-2-1 technique works by pulling your brain out of the future and anchoring it back into the present moment through your five senses.\n\nThe process starts with sight. By identifying five distinct objects around you—a lamp, a crack in the wall, a distant tree—you engage the prefrontal cortex of your brain. This area is responsible for logical thinking and begins to override the 'amygdala,' which is the alarm center of your brain. By focusing on external details, you signal to your nervous system that you are in a safe environment.\n\nAs you move through touch, sound, and smell, your heart rate naturally begins to slow down. Touching 4 different textures, like the roughness of your denim jeans or the cool surface of a table, activates the somatosensory cortex. This shift in focus reduces the 'noise' of anxious thoughts. By the time you reach the final step—tasting one thing—the biological 'fight or flight' response has usually diminished significantly.\n\nTo make this most effective, try to describe the objects in detail in your mind. Don't just see a chair; see a 'brown wooden chair with a curved back.' The more detail you provide, the more 'processing power' your brain has to use, leaving less room for anxious loops.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Navy SEAL Box Breathing',
    description: 'Control your stress like a professional.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506126613408-eca07ce68773?w=500',
    content: "Box breathing, also known as four-square breathing, is a technique used by high-performance professionals like Navy SEALs to stay calm under immense pressure. It works by regulating your autonomic nervous system and physically forcing your heart rate to slow down by increasing the CO2 levels in your blood slightly, which triggers a relaxation response.\n\nThe technique is simple: Inhale for 4 seconds, hold for 4, exhale for 4, and hold for 4. When you hold your breath, you allow CO2 to build up, which stimulates the vagus nerve. This nerve is the 'on-off switch' for your body's relaxation response. It sends a direct signal to your brain that it is time to exit the 'fight-or-flight' mode and enter the 'rest-and-digest' state.\n\nPsychologically, the act of counting provides a rhythmic focus that distracts the mind from intrusive thoughts. It gives you a sense of control over a body that feels like it is spinning out of control. Many people find that doing just four rounds of this cycle is enough to stop a rising panic attack in its tracks.\n\nYou can practice this anywhere—in a meeting, on a bus, or before an exam. Because it is a silent and internal process, it is your secret weapon against sudden anxiety spikes.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Is it Intuition or Just Anxiety?',
    description: 'Learn to distinguish between fear and wisdom.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1499209974431-9ddd3e2f01f2?w=500',
    content: "One of the most confusing parts of living with anxiety is that it often feels like a 'gut feeling' or intuition. However, mistaking anxiety for intuition can lead to a cycle of avoidance and fear. Understanding the biological and psychological differences between the two is key to reclaiming your peace of mind.\n\nAnxiety is almost always rooted in fear and 'what-if' scenarios. It feels loud, frantic, and repetitive. Physically, anxiety shows up as tension in the chest, a racing heart, or a sinking feeling in the stomach. It pushes you to act immediately to avoid a perceived disaster. It is a chaotic energy that leaves you feeling drained and uncertain.\n\nIn contrast, intuition is quiet, calm, and certain. It doesn't scream at you; it simply 'knows.' Intuition feels like a neutral pull toward or away from something, whereas anxiety feels like a push from behind. Intuition remains consistent over time, while anxiety fluctuates based on your stress levels and surroundings. Intuition provides clarity, even if the answer isn't what you wanted to hear.\n\nNext time you feel a strong urge or fear, pause and ask yourself: 'Is this message coming from a place of peace or a place of panic?' If it’s loud and scary, it’s likely anxiety. If it’s quiet and steady, it’s likely your intuition. Taking this moment to differentiate allows you to act from a place of wisdom rather than reaction.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Digital Detox for Mental Peace',
    description: 'Why your phone is fueling your worry.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516387933964-b834633b4009?w=500',
    content: "Our brains were not evolved to handle the 24/7 stream of information, tragedies, and social comparisons that a smartphone provides. Every notification, like or headline triggers a small hit of dopamine or a spike of cortisol. Over time, this constant stimulation keeps your brain in a state of high alert, making you more prone to chronic anxiety.\n\nThe term 'Doomscrolling' describes the act of continuously scrolling through bad news, even though it makes us feel worse. This behavior is an evolutionary glitch; our ancestors needed to know about threats to survive. Today, however, we are exposed to threats from across the globe that we cannot control. This creates a sense of 'learned helplessness,' a core component of clinical anxiety.\n\nTo break this cycle, you need a structured digital detox. Start by turning off all non-essential notifications. Designate 'phone-free zones' in your house, like the dinner table or your bedroom. By physically removing the device, you allow your brain's 'Default Mode Network' to activate. This is the state where your mind can process thoughts calmly and creatively without being interrupted by external pings.\n\nEven a 30-minute break from your screen can lower your resting heart rate and reduce feelings of 'FOMO' (Fear Of Missing Out). When you put down the phone, you pick up your life. You begin to notice the real world around you, which is almost always much calmer and safer than the digital world inside your screen.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'The Power of Reframing Thoughts',
    description: 'Changing your "What-ifs" into "Even-ifs".',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1493839523149-2864fca44919?w=500',
    content: "Cognitive Reframing is a pillar of Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT). It involves identifying a negative thought and challenging its validity. Anxiety loves the 'What-if' game: What if I lose my job? What if they don't like me? What if I fail the exam? These thoughts create a mental movie of a future that hasn't happened yet.\n\nThe first step in reframing is to catch the thought. Imagine the thought is a person talking to you. Is this person being helpful, or are they just being a bully? Once you identify the 'What-if,' try to counter it with a 'So what?' or an 'Even-if.' For example, 'What if I fail the exam?' becomes 'Even if I fail, I am still a capable person and I can retake it.'\n\nThis shift from 'What-if' to 'Even-if' is powerful because it acknowledges the worst-case scenario but removes its power over you. You are telling your brain that you are resilient enough to handle whatever happens. This reduces the need for the brain to keep sending you alarm signals (anxiety) because the 'threat' is no longer seen as a total catastrophe.\n\nPractice this daily with small worries. If you worry about being late, tell yourself, 'Even if I am late, I will apologize and the day will continue.' Over time, you will train your brain to be a problem-solver rather than a disaster-imaginer. You will find that most of the things you worry about never happen, and the things that do happen, you are strong enough to handle.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Magnesium and Your Nerves',
    description: 'The nutritional link to anxiety.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1550989460-0adf9ea622e2?w=500',
    content: "Often, what we feel as mental anxiety is actually a physical deficiency in the body. Magnesium is a vital mineral that plays a role in over 300 biochemical reactions in the human body, including the regulation of the nervous system. It is often called 'nature's relaxant' because it helps block stimulating neurotransmitters and binds to calming receptors in the brain.\n\nWhen you are stressed, your body 'wastes' magnesium by flushing it out through your urine. This creates a vicious cycle: stress causes low magnesium, and low magnesium makes you more sensitive to stress. Symptoms of low magnesium often mimic anxiety—muscle twitches, heart palpitations, insomnia, and a constant feeling of 'edginess.'\n\nTo break this cycle, you can focus on magnesium-rich foods like spinach, almonds, black beans, and dark chocolate. Some people find that taking a magnesium glycinate supplement before bed helps them sleep more deeply and feel calmer the next day. However, always consult with a doctor before starting any new supplement.\n\nBeyond just food, even an Epsom salt bath can help. Epsom salt is magnesium sulfate, which can be absorbed through the skin. The combination of warm water and magnesium works together to relax your muscles and signal to your brain that the day is over and it is safe to rest. Taking care of your body's chemistry is a huge step in taking care of your mind.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'The "Brain Dump" Journaling',
    description: 'Emptying your mental trash can.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1517842645537-4d25890bb892?w=500',
    content: "Anxiety often feels like having fifty browser tabs open in your brain at once. Each tab is a task, a worry, or a memory competing for your attention. This creates 'mental clutter' that makes it impossible to focus or feel at peace. A 'Brain Dump' is a simple journaling exercise designed to close those tabs and clear your mental cache.\n\nTo do a brain dump, take a piece of paper and a pen. Set a timer for 5 or 10 minutes. Now, write down everything that is currently in your head. Don't worry about grammar, spelling, or making sense. Write down chores you need to do, people you are annoyed with, fears about the future, and even random thoughts like 'I need to buy milk.'\n\nThe goal is to get the thoughts out of your head and onto the paper. Once a thought is written down, the brain feels it has 'stored' the information and no longer needs to keep looping it in your active memory. You will notice an almost immediate sense of lightness in your forehead and chest as you do this.\n\nAfter the timer goes off, look at the list. You will likely see that most of your 'major' worries are actually small tasks or unfounded fears. You can now cross off the things you can't control and make a plan for the things you can. This exercise turns a chaotic 'feeling' of anxiety into a manageable 'list' of facts.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Weighted Blankets: The Science',
    description: 'Why physical pressure calms the mind.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1520699049698-acd2fccb8cc8?w=500',
    content: "Have you ever wondered why a hug feels so good when you're stressed? The reason is a biological phenomenon called 'Deep Pressure Touch' (DPT). This is a form of firm but gentle pressure that stimulates the release of serotonin and dopamine while decreasing cortisol levels. Weighted blankets use this same science to help people with anxiety feel safe and grounded.\n\nWhen you lie under a weighted blanket, the pressure signals to your brain that you are being 'held' or protected. This triggers the parasympathetic nervous system, which is responsible for the 'rest and digest' state. For many people with anxiety, their nervous system is 'hyper-aroused,' meaning it's always looking for danger. The weight of the blanket acts as a physical anchor that tells the system: 'You are safe. You can stop looking for threats.'\n\nStudies have shown that using a weighted blanket can significantly reduce night-time anxiety and insomnia. By providing a consistent sensory input, it prevents the body from tossing and turning, which in turn prevents the mind from wandering into anxious loops. It's like a constant, gentle hug that lasts all night long.\n\nIf you don't have a weighted blanket, you can achieve a similar effect by using several heavy quilts or even placing a pillow across your chest while you lie down. The key is the sensation of pressure. It’s a simple, non-medicinal way to tell your body that it’s okay to let go of the day’s tension.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Social Anxiety Survival Guide',
    description: 'How to navigate crowds with ease.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1523240795612-9a054b0db644?w=500',
    content: "Social anxiety is often driven by the 'Spotlight Effect'—the belief that everyone is watching you and judging your every move. In reality, most people are far too worried about themselves to notice your small awkward moments. Realizing that you are not the center of everyone else's judgment is the first step toward social freedom.\n\nA great hack for social anxiety is the 'Curiosity Shift.' Instead of focusing on how you are appearing to others, shift your focus to being curious about them. Ask open-ended questions like 'How do you know the host?' or 'What’s the best thing that happened to you this week?' When you are genuinely curious about someone else, your brain doesn't have the capacity to be self-conscious.\n\nAnother tip is to have an 'exit strategy.' Knowing that you can leave a situation whenever you want provides a sense of control. You don't have to stay at a party for three hours; you can tell yourself you'll stay for twenty minutes, and if you're still uncomfortable, you're allowed to go home. Ironically, having the permission to leave often makes you feel comfortable enough to stay.\n\nFinally, remember that 'awkwardness' is a shared human experience. Everyone has said the wrong thing or tripped over their words. If you make a mistake, acknowledge it with a small laugh and move on. People don't remember your mistakes; they remember how you made them feel. If you are kind and attentive, they will walk away with a positive impression of you.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'The Morning Courage Ritual',
    description: 'Setting a brave tone for your day.',
    moodTag: 'Anxious',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1470252649358-96957c7d31d7?w=500',
    content: "For many people, anxiety is at its highest the moment they wake up. This is due to the 'Cortisol Awakening Response' (CAR), where the body naturally spikes stress hormones to help you wake up. If you already have an anxious mind, this spike can feel like a wave of dread about the coming day. To combat this, you need a 'Courage Ritual.'\n\nAvoid your phone for the first 15 minutes of the day. Checking emails or news immediately feeds your cortisol spike with more reasons to worry. Instead, spend those first few minutes doing something grounding. This could be stretching, drinking a glass of water, or simply sitting on the edge of your bed and noticing your breath. You are teaching your brain that you are in charge of the day's pace.\n\nIncorporate 'Affirmations of Capability' into your morning. This isn't about 'everything will be perfect.' It’s about saying: 'Whatever happens today, I am capable of handling it.' This builds self-efficacy—the belief in your own ability to succeed. When you believe you can handle the challenges, the challenges themselves become less scary.\n\nLastly, try a 'Cold Splash.' Splashing ice-cold water on your face for 30 seconds triggers the 'Mammalian Dive Reflex.' This reflex instantly lowers your heart rate and resets your nervous system. It’s a physical 'reset button' that can clear away the morning fog of anxiety and help you start your day from a place of strength.",
  ),
  // --- SAD ---
  // ================= SAD ARTICLES (10) =================
  Article(
    title: 'The Biological Purpose of Tears',
    description: 'Why crying is a natural detox for your brain.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1499209974431-9ddd3e2f01f2?w=500',
    content: "In many cultures, crying is wrongly seen as a sign of weakness or loss of control. However, biology tells a completely different story. Emotional tears contain higher levels of stress hormones, specifically cortisol and leucine-enkephalin (a natural painkiller), than tears caused by physical irritants like onions.\n\nWhen you allow yourself to cry because of sadness, you are quite literally flushing stress chemicals out of your body. This is a biological safety valve that prevents your nervous system from becoming overloaded. This is why people often report feeling 'lighter' or experiencing a sense of 'catharsis' after a deep cry. It’s not just a feeling; it’s a physical reset.\n\nTears also trigger the release of oxytocin and endorphins, our body's natural feel-good chemicals. These chemicals help ease both physical and emotional pain, providing a soothing effect that stabilizes your mood. By holding in tears, you are essentially keeping stress hormones trapped inside your system.\n\nNext time you feel the urge to cry, don’t fight it. Find a safe space and let the process happen. Your body knows how to heal itself if you allow it to move through the emotion rather than blocking it. Crying is not falling apart; it is a vital step in the process of putting yourself back together.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Understanding "Low Power Mode"',
    description: 'Why sadness makes you feel physically heavy.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516589174184-c68543c162fe?w=500',
    content: "When you are going through a period of deep sadness or grief, even simple tasks like washing your face or making a meal can feel like climbing a mountain. This heavy, sluggish feeling is often confusing and can lead to self-criticism. However, from an evolutionary perspective, this is your brain entering a necessary 'Low Power Mode.'\n\nEvolutionary psychology suggests that sadness forces us to withdraw and conserve energy. This withdrawal serves a purpose: it signals to your brain that it needs to stop focusing on external activities and start focusing on internal healing. Just as a phone slows down when its battery is low to prevent a total shutdown, your mind slows you down to process complex emotional changes or loss.\n\nDuring this time, your brain is engaged in 'analytical rumination.' This is a state where the mind works through the problems or events that led to the sadness. By making you feel tired and heavy, your body is ensuring that you stay still long enough for this mental processing to take place. It is a protective mechanism designed to help you navigate a difficult transition.\n\nRespect your need for rest during these times. Don't call yourself lazy; call yourself 'recovering.' Give your mind the grace to move at a slower pace. The energy will return, but only after the emotional heavy lifting has been completed.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'The Myth of Linear Healing',
    description: 'Why progress often feels like two steps back.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1502135328448-f32617637894?w=500',
    content: "We are often sold a false narrative that recovery from sadness should be a straight line moving upward. In reality, healing is a messy, circular, and unpredictable process. You might have three good days followed by a week that feels like you're back at square one. This doesn't mean you aren't healing; it just means you're human.\n\nThink of healing like the tide of the ocean. Sometimes the water comes in high, and sometimes it recedes. Even when the tide is out, the ocean is still there, moving and changing. On your 'bad' days, it’s easy to feel like all your progress has vanished. But those bad days are actually when the most profound emotional integration is happening. You are building resilience every time you face a difficult day and make it to the next morning.\n\nOne of the most dangerous things you can do is compare your 'middle' to someone else’s 'end.' Everyone’s timeline for sadness is different. Some people process quickly, while others need months or years. Neither way is superior. The key is to stop judging your progress based on how you feel in a single moment.\n\nKeep a 'Small Wins' log. On the days you feel you've regressed, look back at the week and notice the tiny moments of strength you showed. Healing isn't the absence of sadness; it is the ability to carry sadness while still moving forward, one step at a time.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Small Wins in Big Shadows',
    description: 'Celebrating micro-victories when energy is low.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1490730141103-6cac27aaab94?w=500',
    content: "When deep sadness hits, the 'all-or-nothing' thinking takes over. We feel like if we aren't 100% productive or happy, the whole day is a waste. This mindset makes the shadow of sadness feel even bigger than it is. To combat this, we must learn the art of celebrating 'Micro-Wins.'\n\nA Micro-Win is any small action that requires effort when you are feeling low. Did you drink a glass of water? Did you step outside for sixty seconds? Did you answer one text message? These aren't just 'chores'; they are massive victories of the will over a heavy mood. Each time you complete a small task, you signal to your brain that you still have a level of agency over your life.\n\nBiologically, completing even a tiny task releases a minute amount of dopamine. While it might not make you feel 'happy' instantly, it helps slowly rebuild the motivation pathways in your brain that sadness has dampened. It is like trying to start a fire with damp wood; you need a lot of tiny sparks before you get a steady flame.\n\nLower your expectations for yourself on dark days. If all you did today was survive, that is enough. Tomorrow is another opportunity for a few more sparks. You are not defined by your productivity; you are defined by your persistence.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'The Art of Writing to the Void',
    description: 'How letters you never send can set you free.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1455390582262-044cdead277a?w=500',
    content: "When we are sad, there is often a lot of 'unspoken energy' trapped in our minds—things we wish we had said, apologies we never got, or anger we can't express. This trapped energy keeps the sadness looping. 'Writing to the Void' is a psychological technique where you write a letter that you have no intention of ever sending.\n\nAddress the letter to a person, a situation, or even to your own sadness. Say exactly how you feel. Don't hold back. Use the words you were afraid to say. The act of moving these thoughts from the abstract space of your mind onto a physical piece of paper creates a 'psychological distance.' It turns the internal chaos into an external object that you can observe.\n\nOnce the letter is finished, you can do whatever you want with it. Some people find peace in tearing it up, while others prefer to burn it in a safe place. This symbolic act of 'releasing' the paper helps the brain finalize the emotional experience. It signals that the message has been delivered, even if the recipient never sees it.\n\nThis isn't about the other person; it's about your own closure. You are clearing out the emotional archives of your mind to make room for new experiences. It is a private, powerful way to honor your feelings without the fear of judgment or confrontation.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Nutrition for a Heavy Heart',
    description: 'Foods that support your brain during sadness.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512621776951-a57141f2eefd?w=500',
    content: "While food cannot 'cure' sadness, there is a strong link between your gut health and your mood. About 95% of your serotonin—the hormone that stabilizes mood and feelings of well-being—is produced in your gastrointestinal tract. When you are sad, your body often craves high-sugar 'comfort foods,' but these often lead to a crash that makes you feel worse.\n\nTo support your brain during low periods, focus on Omega-3 fatty acids found in fish, walnuts, and flaxseeds. Omega-3s are essential for brain cell communication and have been shown in studies to reduce symptoms of depression. Similarly, B vitamins found in leafy greens and eggs are crucial for producing brain chemicals that affect mood.\n\nComplex carbohydrates, like oats and whole grains, can also be helpful. Unlike simple sugars, complex carbs are digested slowly, providing a steady stream of energy and helping your brain produce serotonin without the 'spike and crash' cycle. Even small dietary shifts can make a difference in your baseline energy levels.\n\nDon't force yourself into a strict diet when you're already struggling. Instead, try the 'Add-One' rule. If you're eating a meal, just add one healthy thing to it—a handful of spinach or a few walnuts. Taking care of your biology is a form of self-love that tells your brain it is worth being cared for.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Pet Therapy: Unconditional Love',
    description: 'The healing power of a silent companion.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1495360010541-f48722b34f7d?w=500',
    content: "One of the hardest parts of sadness is the feeling of being judged or misunderstood by others. This is why the bond with a pet can be so incredibly healing. Animals don't ask for explanations. They don't tell you to 'just cheer up.' They simply exist with you, offering a presence that is both silent and supportive.\n\nInteracting with a pet—whether it's stroking a cat's fur or playing with a dog—lowers your blood pressure and releases oxytocin. This hormone reduces stress and creates a sense of belonging and safety. For someone struggling with sadness, the responsibility of caring for a pet can also provide a gentle 'nudge' to maintain a routine, which is vital for mental health.\n\nEven if you don't own a pet, spending time in environments with animals can have a similar effect. Observing birds in a park or visiting a cat cafe provides a sensory distraction that pulls you out of your internal rumination. It reminds you that life is happening all around you in simple, uncomplicated ways.\n\nAnimals provide 'unconditional positive regard.' They see you as you are, without your titles, your achievements, or your current mood. In their eyes, you are always enough. Allowing yourself to receive that simple, pure affection can be a powerful antidote to the isolation that sadness often brings.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'Sunlight and Serotonin',
    description: 'The simple science of Vitamin D and mood.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1444491741275-3747c53c99b4?w=500',
    content: "It is not a coincidence that many people feel sadder during the winter months or when they spend too much time indoors. Our bodies are deeply connected to the rhythm of the sun. Sunlight triggers the brain to release a hormone called serotonin, which is associated with boosting mood and helping a person feel calm and focused.\n\nWithout enough sun exposure, your serotonin levels can dip, leading to a higher risk of 'Seasonal Affective Disorder' (SAD) or general lethargy. Sunlight also helps regulate your circadian rhythm—your internal clock. When this clock is in sync, you sleep better, and better sleep is one of the most effective tools for managing emotional heaviness.\n\nTry to get at least 15 minutes of direct sunlight every morning. Even if it's cloudy, the natural light is much stronger than indoor lighting. Open your curtains as soon as you wake up. If you're stuck in an office, try to take your lunch break near a window.\n\nThink of sunlight as a 'nutrient' for your brain. You wouldn't go days without water; try not to go days without light. This small, physical shift can help signal to your brain that it is time to wake up and engage with the world, even if only for a few minutes.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'The Value of "Sad" Music',
    description: 'Why listening to sad songs makes us feel better.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1459749411177-042180ce673c?w=500',
    content: "It seems counterintuitive, but when we are sad, we often reach for sad music. You might think this would make you feel worse, but research shows it actually has a healing effect. Sad music provides a sense of 'vicarious emotion'—it allows you to experience sadness without the actual threat of the situation that caused it.\n\nListening to a sad song creates a feeling of connection. It tells you that someone else has felt exactly what you are feeling and has turned that pain into something beautiful. This reduces the feeling of isolation. You realize that your experience is a shared human one. The music becomes a 'virtual friend' that understands you when words fail.\n\nBiologically, sad music can trigger the release of prolactin, a hormone associated with weeping and a sense of consolation. It’s as if the brain is trying to prepare you for a traumatic event, but since no actual trauma is happening, you are left with a soothing 'hormonal hug.'\n\nDon't feel bad about playing that melancholy playlist on repeat. If it helps you cry, or if it helps you feel seen, then it is doing its job. Music is a bridge that carries us from the depth of an emotion back to the surface.",
  ),
  Article(
    title: 'When to Seek Extra Support',
    description: 'Understanding the line between sadness and depression.',
    moodTag: 'Sad',
    imageUrl: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1527137342181-19aab11a8ee1?w=500',
    content: "Sadness is a normal part of life, but it’s important to know when it has shifted into something that requires professional help. If your sadness has lasted for more than two weeks, if you’ve lost interest in everything you used to love, or if you feel a sense of hopelessness that won't lift, it may be time to talk to a therapist.\n\nThere is no shame in seeking help. Just as you would go to a doctor for a broken bone, you should see a mental health professional for an overwhelmed mind. Therapy provides you with a 'toolbox' of strategies to navigate your emotions. It gives you a safe space to unpack your thoughts without judgment.\n\nSometimes, sadness is caused by a chemical imbalance that requires more than just 'positive thinking.' In these cases, a combination of therapy and sometimes medication can be life-changing. You don't have to carry the weight of the world on your own shoulders.\n\nReaching out is an act of bravery. It shows that you value yourself enough to fight for your well-being. Whether it's a counselor, a support group, or a trusted doctor, there are people who are trained and ready to help you find your way back to the light.",
  ),
